WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.950 --> 00:00:06.200
Jojen Paste is a Game of Thrones fan theory
claiming that Bran eats Jojen. Which sounds

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:11.610
crazy, but may actually be true – so let’s
have a look. In season 4 of Game of Thrones

00:00:11.610 --> 00:00:17.190
and Book 5 of A Song of Ice and Fire, Bran
Stark travels north, with Jojen, Meera, Hodor,

00:00:17.190 --> 00:00:22.670
and, in the books, Coldhands, a mysterious
walking corpse. They go to the home of the

00:00:22.670 --> 00:00:27.529
three-eyed crow, or Bloodraven, a “Dreamer,
wizard [and] greenseer” connected to the

00:00:27.529 --> 00:00:32.509
weirwoods and the children of the forest and
the magic of the old gods. The point of all

00:00:32.509 --> 00:00:37.460
this, apparently, is for Bloodraven to teach
Bran to use the magic power of the old gods,

00:00:37.460 --> 00:00:42.469
the powers of a greenseer. So in Dance, we
get a sort of a training montage, kinda like

00:00:42.469 --> 00:00:47.710
Luke Skywalker’s training in Star Wars – amongst
darkness and twisted tree-roots, an old but

00:00:47.710 --> 00:00:53.280
powerful mentor trains a young hero to unlock
his mystical powers. Bran learns to see into

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:57.390
the past through the eyes of weirwood trees
, and to better skinchange – enter the minds

00:00:57.390 --> 00:01:02.039
of animals . As part of this training, Bloodraven
and the children of the forest give Bran a

00:01:02.039 --> 00:01:07.150
bowl of white paste apparently made out of
weirwood seeds. It’s “thick and heavy,

00:01:07.150 --> 00:01:11.909
with dark red veins running through it”
that look “remarkably like blood” . Apparently

00:01:11.909 --> 00:01:17.110
the purpose of this paste is to “help awaken
[Bran’s] gifts and wed [him] to the trees”

00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:21.560
. So Bran eats it, then has a vision through
the eyes of a weirwood tree. Afterwards, he

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:27.009
finds Jojen and Meera curiously absent . He
then has more visions, and the chapter ends,

00:01:27.009 --> 00:01:30.920
and that’s the last we’ve seen of Bran.
So the Jojen Paste theory claims that the

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:37.470
weirwood paste that Bran eats actually contains
the blood or body of Jojen. So – what’s

00:01:37.470 --> 00:01:41.119
the evidence?
Firstly, the tone of this whole chapter is

00:01:41.119 --> 00:01:46.509
really really dark and ominous. Its imagery
includes “dead men”, “dark clouds”,

00:01:46.509 --> 00:01:49.920
“blood stew”, “murder”s of crows,
“chambers … of bones”, a “talking

00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:53.899
corpse” and “whispers in the dark”,
it’s like a Halloween haunted house in here.

00:01:53.899 --> 00:01:59.890
There’s particular emphasis on flesh , and
blood , and knives – the line “The moon

00:01:59.890 --> 00:02:04.530
was a crescent, thin and sharp as the blade
of a knife” appears four times in this chapter,

00:02:04.530 --> 00:02:09.610
as the phases of the moon are used to track
the passage of time. So the tone and the imagery

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:15.160
of this chapter really set the scene for something
bad to happen, maybe something involving knives

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:19.319
and flesh and blood.
And it’s strongly implied that something

00:02:19.319 --> 00:02:24.420
bad is going to happen to Jojen. Of course,
in the show, Jojen is already dead. He’s

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:28.650
stabbed, then mercy-killed, then blown up
by a child of the forest, cause apparently

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:33.239
that’s what you do, but in the books, Jojen
survives the wights, and while Bran trains,

00:02:33.239 --> 00:02:38.910
he mopes around Bloodraven’s cave, growing
“ever more sullen and solitary” . “Food

00:02:38.910 --> 00:02:42.250
and … rest” improve his physical health
“after … their journey, but he [seems]

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:47.840
sadder now, sullen, with a weary, haunted
look about the eyes” . At one point he implies

00:02:47.840 --> 00:02:53.250
that he has reason to be afraid . And this
seems to be related to his greensight – his

00:02:53.250 --> 00:02:58.280
prophetic dreams of the future. Meera says
Jojen “will not even try and fight his fate.

00:02:58.280 --> 00:03:03.680
He says the greendreams do not lie” . Jojen
has hinted that he’s foreseen his own death

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:08.780
in his dreams . What seems to be going on
here is that Jojen is upset because he knows

00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:13.409
his death is coming. So why might Jojen have
to die?

00:03:13.409 --> 00:03:18.530
Jojen’s job is to bring Bran to Bloodraven
so Bloodraven can teach Bran to use the magic

00:03:18.530 --> 00:03:23.879
of the old gods. But magic in A Song of Ice
and Fire is not some Harry Potter swish-and-flick

00:03:23.879 --> 00:03:29.620
bullshit, magic in this world is messy and
ugly and it often has a price. When Daenerys

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:34.430
uses magic to try to keep Drogo alive, the
price is the life of a horse – and of Dany’s

00:03:34.430 --> 00:03:40.030
unborn child. Melisandre needs king’s blood
and the burning of innocents to work her magic

00:03:40.030 --> 00:03:44.480
. Euron Greyjoy makes blood sacrifices to
make his ships sail faster . And there are

00:03:44.480 --> 00:03:48.680
many other examples from many different cultures
all across the world of ice and fire of the

00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:54.200
need for human sacrifice, or blood sacrifice,
in magic . So it makes a lot of sense that

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:58.319
awakening Bran’s magic would also require
human sacrifice – especially when we’re

00:03:58.319 --> 00:04:02.830
talking about the magic of the old gods – we’re
told repeatedly that northmen used to make

00:04:02.830 --> 00:04:07.640
human sacrifices to the weirwoods – and
the Skagosi apparently still do . Further,

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:12.290
Bran’s last vision in this chapter is of
a woman slashing a captive’s throat before

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:17.669
a weirwood tree, and “as his life flow[s]
out of him in a red tide”, Bran can “taste

00:04:17.669 --> 00:04:22.669
the blood” . So in the same chapter where
Bran eats the suspiciously bloody weirwood

00:04:22.669 --> 00:04:26.880
paste to awaken his magic, we’re reminded
of the connections between the magic of the

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:32.229
old gods and the weirwoods and human sacrifice.
Further, with human sacrifice and blood magic,

00:04:32.229 --> 00:04:36.919
one person’s blood can be more powerful
than another’s – for example, Melisandre

00:04:36.919 --> 00:04:41.210
specifically needs king’s blood for her
most powerful magic. This might explain why

00:04:41.210 --> 00:04:45.720
Jojen’s blood is needed, rather than Meera’s,
or Hodor’s, because while Jojen isn’t

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:50.570
a fully-fledged greenseer like Bloodraven,
he does have green dreams, prophetic dreams

00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:55.889
, and special moss-green eyes that mark his
gift . Jojen has the power of the old gods

00:04:55.889 --> 00:05:01.970
in his blood, so it makes sense that his sacrifice
specifically has the power to awaken Bran’s

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:04.800
magic.
Another thing that’s going on here if Jojen

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:10.610
Paste is real is cannibalism. And cannibalism
is a recurring theme in the north – Stannis’

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:16.389
starving soldiers eat their own fallen , Wyman
Manderley bakes Freys into pies, Varamyr eats

00:05:16.389 --> 00:05:21.870
human flesh while warged into his wolf . And
cannibalism, especially unknowing cannibalism,

00:05:21.870 --> 00:05:26.889
is a recurring theme specifically in Bran’s
chapters. When Bran is at the Nightfort, he

00:05:26.889 --> 00:05:31.650
recalls the tale of the Rat Cook , who cooked
an Andal prince in a pie and served him to

00:05:31.650 --> 00:05:36.759
his father, then was cursed to live as a rat,
eating his own young . In the cave of the

00:05:36.759 --> 00:05:42.710
three-eyed crow, Bran and co. eat suspicious
meat that might be squirrel, or rat, or maybe

00:05:42.710 --> 00:05:47.460
something else … And when Bran is travelling
north, Coldhands feeds him the flesh of some

00:05:47.460 --> 00:05:52.509
Night’s Watchmen and tells him that it’s
pork . Also, like Varamyr, Bran eats human

00:05:52.509 --> 00:05:57.990
flesh while warged into his wolf . So Bran
has already eaten human meat – snacking

00:05:57.990 --> 00:06:03.509
on some Jojen would be just one more example
of cannibalism in his chapters. Further, on

00:06:03.509 --> 00:06:08.120
the journey north, Bran and co. eat Coldhands’
elk, which Bran feels guilty about because

00:06:08.120 --> 00:06:13.770
he considers the elk a “friend” . So Bran
has not only already been eating human flesh,

00:06:13.770 --> 00:06:19.120
but he’s already been eating his friends.
So the pieces are starting to come together.

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:22.889
This chapter is really dark and ominous, it’s
strongly hinted that something bad will happen

00:06:22.889 --> 00:06:28.460
to Jojen, it makes sense that Bran’s magical
awakening would require blood sacrifice, cannibalism

00:06:28.460 --> 00:06:33.389
is a theme of Bran’s chapters. It looks
like – maybe – Bloodraven and the children

00:06:33.389 --> 00:06:37.780
of the forest secretly kill Jojen and put
his blood in the weirwood paste that they

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:44.810
feed to Bran in order to awaken Bran’s magic.
But does that fit with what we know of Bloodraven?

00:06:44.810 --> 00:06:50.360
Bloodraven doesn’t exactly seem like a good
guy – just look at him – he’s a hundred-and-twenty-five-year-old

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:56.199
“half-corpse and half-tree”, with “weirwood
roots [snaking] in and out of his withered

00:06:56.199 --> 00:07:01.000
flesh”. He’s “less a man than some ghastly
statue made of twisted wood, old bone, and

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.840
rotted wool” . He lives in a cave full of
creepy forest elf children and “the bones

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:11.349
of thousands dead” – his home is literally
littered with human skulls . And look at the

00:07:11.349 --> 00:07:15.880
shit he says – “Never fear the darkness,
Bran … Darkness will make you strong”

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:21.160
. To return to the Star Wars comparison, Bloodraven
is much less like Yoda than he’s like Vader

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:27.190
or the Emperor. He’s dark, seductive, manipulative,
and deceptive. Bran thought Bloodraven would

00:07:27.190 --> 00:07:31.470
be “a wise old wizard who could fix his
legs” , he never signed up to become a psychic

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:36.229
tree . And what about Jojen, Meera and Hodor,
what’s gonna happen to them? They can hardly

00:07:36.229 --> 00:07:40.690
return to the Wall with winter setting in.
Maybe Bloodraven has good reasons for all

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:46.090
this. Leaf says he works “For us, for you,
for the realms of men” , but even if that’s

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:50.360
true, Bloodraven really doesn’t seem to
have Bran, Jojen, Meera and Hodor’s best

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:55.419
interests at heart. He risks their lives bringing
them to his cave, he never explains what it

00:07:55.419 --> 00:08:00.120
is that he wants, and he’s turning Bran
into something that he never wanted to become.

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:04.940
If sacrificing Jojen was necessary for Bloodraven’s
goals, it’s easy to believe that he’d

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:08.750
do it.
Finally, this theory could fit well with Bran’s

00:08:08.750 --> 00:08:13.729
character arc. Bran starts the story as a
boy who dreams of being a heroic knight like

00:08:13.729 --> 00:08:18.800
in the fairy tales , just like Sansa dreams
of being a noble lady. Both of these characters

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:23.139
get what they wish for – Sansa courts a
prince in the royal castle , and Bran journeys

00:08:23.139 --> 00:08:28.130
into danger in search of a magical power.
But Sansa soon realises that the world that

00:08:28.130 --> 00:08:33.260
she dreamed of is actually pretty terrible.
Joffrey’s a “monster” , and Cersei’s

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:38.880
a – quote – “vile, scheming, evil bitch”
. Bran is starting to make a similar realisation

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:43.050
– Coldhands is a “monster” , and the
mystical three-eyed crow is actually a creepy

00:08:43.050 --> 00:08:49.380
half-corpse tree-man. Maybe part of this disillusionment
for Bran will be the horrific discovery that

00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:53.970
he ate his friend. And there are a bunch of
interesting ways that could go – maybe,

00:08:53.970 --> 00:08:58.459
after finding out, Bran would try to get away
from Bloodraven – which might be difficult

00:08:58.459 --> 00:09:03.410
for someone who can’t walk – or maybe
he’ll embrace the darkness anyway. Bran

00:09:03.410 --> 00:09:07.930
has done some messed-up stuff lately, like
warging into Hodor all the time even though

00:09:07.930 --> 00:09:12.980
it clearly makes Hodor distressed . However
bad this Bloodraven stuff is, it empowers

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:17.480
Bran at a time when he’s frustrated by his
helplessness – maybe he’d be too immersed

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:23.080
in his greenseer power to notice or care about
the death of Jojen. Another interesting factor

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:27.880
here is that Bran has a crush on Meera . How
would Meera react to Jojen’s death, and

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:32.850
how would Bran react to Meera? And what will
happen to poor Hodor? There are lots of different

00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:37.010
ways this could work, but the point is that
Jojen Paste could fit into Bran’s story

00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:42.660
in some really interesting ways, possibly
as part of a turn towards darkness.

00:09:42.660 --> 00:09:49.800
So. Is there any strong direct evidence that
Bran eats Jojen? No. There’s no strong evidence

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:55.220
against it, either. But here’s what we do
know. In an extremely dark and ominous chapter,

00:09:55.220 --> 00:10:00.800
it’s strongly implied that Jojen knows his
death is coming. Bran eats a suspiciously

00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:06.260
bloody weirwood paste, and afterwards Jojen
and Meera seem to be gone. The paste is meant

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:11.870
to awaken Bran’s magic power, and we know
blood sacrifice is often needed to work magic,

00:10:11.870 --> 00:10:17.040
especially the magic of the old gods and the
weirwoods. Cannibalism is a recurring theme

00:10:17.040 --> 00:10:22.399
in Bran’s chapters, with Bran having already
eaten the flesh of humans and of friends.

00:10:22.399 --> 00:10:27.220
Bloodraven is a creepy, nasty dude who seems
willing to put his goals above the safety

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:32.920
of others, and Bran’s story seems to be
heading towards a confrontation with the darkness.

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:38.870
So there’s nothing concrete here, but the
pieces do seem to fit. It seems very plausible,

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:45.880
likely, even, that Bran unknowingly eats Jojen
in Bloodraven’s weirwood paste.

